ed States before and during the COVID-19 pandemic, told through the lens of food. It includes a vibrant mix of perspectives from professional food writers, restaurateurs, scholars, and activists, whose stories range from emotional reflections on hardship, loss, and resilience to journalistic investigations of racism in the American food system. Each contribution is accompanied by a recipe of special importance to the author, giving readers a taste of cuisines from around the world. Every essay is accompanied by gorgeous food photography, the authors’ snapshots of pandemic life, and hand-drawn illustrations by Filipino American artist Angelo Dolojan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  afood, food studies, culture, immigrant, migrant, emigrant, expat, cookbook, recipes, covid-19, corona virus, pandemic, lockdown.1 aAgrawal, Geetika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDava, Keenan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolojan, Angelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrumkin Morales, Bonnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleissner, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleissner, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJolly, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKashdan, Harry Eli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKashdan, Harry Eli, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKassis, Reem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/